## ✅ CODE QUALITY

> **AI: Run this checklist mentally before delivering any code. This is not optional.**
> **If any item fails, fix it before showing the code to the user.**

### Pre-output checklist
- [ ] Every function does exactly one thing. If you can describe it with "and", split it.
- [ ] No function longer than ~30 lines. If longer, extract helper functions.
- [ ] No nesting deeper than 3 levels (if / for / try). Use early returns to flatten.
- [ ] No duplicated logic. If the same block appears twice, extract it.
- [ ] No hardcoded values (strings, numbers, URLs, credentials). Use constants or config.
- [ ] All variables and functions named semantically (see Naming Semantics below).
- [ ] No unused variables, imports, or parameters.
- [ ] Error paths handled. No silent failures, no swallowed exceptions.
- [ ] No inline styles or logic-in-templates.
- [ ] New files placed in the correct directory per STRUCTURE MAP rules.

### Naming semantics — enforced
| Identifier type | Rule | Examples |
|----------------|------|---------|
| Functions / methods | Must start with a verb | `getUser`, `validateEmail`, `buildQuery`, `renderCard` |
| Boolean variables | Must start with `is`, `has`, `can`, `should` | `isLoggedIn`, `hasPermission`, `canEdit` |
| Event handlers | Must start with `handle` or `on` | `handleSubmit`, `onClose`, `handleKeyDown` |
| Classes | PascalCase nouns | `UserProfile`, `AuthService`, `CartItem` |
| Constants | SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE | `MAX_RETRIES`, `DEFAULT_TIMEOUT`, `API_BASE_URL` |
| Collections / arrays | Plural nouns | `users`, `filteredResults`, `activeConnections` |
| Callbacks / iterators | Singular of collection | `users.map(user => …)`, `items.forEach(item => …)` |

_AI: If the project uses a different language, apply the same semantic rules with language-appropriate casing._

### Forbidden patterns
> AI: never produce code containing these. If found in existing code, flag as tech debt.

- `any` type (TypeScript / gradual typing)
- `eval()` or `Function()` constructor
- `console.log` left in committed code (use a proper logger)
- Direct DOM manipulation mixed with framework code
- Synchronous file I/O in a server request path
- Secrets or credentials in source code
- SQL strings built by concatenation (use parameterized queries)
- Catching errors and doing nothing (`catch (e) {}`)
- Mutating function arguments
- Boolean parameters that change function behavior (`doSomething(true)`) — use named options object

### Consistency rules
- If a pattern exists in the codebase, match it exactly. Do not introduce a different style.
- If two valid patterns exist, flag the inconsistency and ask which to standardize.
- When adding a new module, check the existing modules of the same type and mirror their structure.
- Do not mix paradigms (e.g., classes and plain functions for the same concern in the same layer).

